@node eng_further "Game on!"


        More Underground Games to play after a game of:
                        « EXCAVATION »


    1. Boulder Dash
    (First Star, 1984)

    Availability: C64, Amiga

Boulder Dash is already a category of its own, truly a legend. There are many
clones for both computers. The basic idea is that it is set in many 2D caves,
which the player must explore and collect diamonds. He has to avoid monsters
such as fireflies and butterflies. Falling rocks were abudant in this game.

    2. Dig Dug
    (somebody, in the beginning of the 1980s)

    Availability: C64, PC, Atari 2600

Dig Dug was a simple multiple-level 2D arcade game, where the player had a
character (maybe mr. Dug himself) and there were some monsters underground. The
player then had to inflate the monsters with his pump until they burst to
death. Probably of Japanese origin.

    3. Diggers
    (Milennium, 1993)

    Availability: Amiga AGA, CD³²

Diggers was the first game to be released first on the CD³². Although I've
never played it, I've based Excavation mainly on its idea. The basic idea is to
have five diggers running in caverns searching for gems. The diggers have got a
life of their own, unlike the excavators in this game.

    4. Dugger
    (Lin-el, in the end of the 1980s)

    Availability: Amiga (possibly ST also)

Dugger was a graphically advanced version of Dig Dug. That's about it.

    5. H.E.R.O.
    (Activision, 1984)

    Availability: C64

H.E.R.O. was a multi-level platform game in which the hero (!) had to go down
to the bottom of each level and interface with some sort of machine. The main
feature was that the hero could fly with a propeller backpack.

    6. Monster Business
    (Eclipse, 1991)

    Availability: Amiga

Another graphically advanced version of Dig Dug, only this time truly a
different version. Introduced platforms to Dig Dug.

    7. Mr. Do! (I think)
    (somebody, in the 1980s)

    Availability: C64? PC?

Mr. Do! was like Dig Dug, only you killed monsters by dropping rocks on them
rather than inflating them. A version for the Amiga has been released in 1995,
called Derring-Do.

    8. Spelunker
    (Brøderbund, 1984)

    Availability: C64

This is my all-time favourite Underground game. It takes place in a cavern at
least a kilometer deep, and is in its basic sense a platform game. Devices
include ladders, lifts and pyramids, and there are two monsters: the
excrementing bird and the Ghost!


RPGs like Dungeon Master and Eye of the Beholder are not counted as Underground
games, since they take place in man-made dungeons rather than natural caverns.
So there.
@endnode
@node eng_underworld "What is the underworld?"

This is a controversial term. It can mean either:
    - the world of criminals
    - or the world deep inside the earth.
This game uses, of course, the latter meaning.

The term is not to be confused with "netherworld", which is, basically, Hell.
@endnode
@node eng_link "No Zelda here"

The Link screen is a link between two Excavators. Here you can transfer things
from one Excavator to another.

Each Excavator has a set of buttons, which allow him to trade things with his
friend.
  To trade @{"Equipment" link "eng_equip"}, just choose the correct Equipment, and use the + and -
